I'll look at the threatened species profiles in the database section. The issue is likely with the click handlers for the specimen cards. Let me examine the code.

Looking at your code, I can see the threatened species grid is populated dynamically, but there are no click event listeners attached to the cards. Here's the fix:

Find this section in your JavaScript (around line 5300-5400) where you create the threatened species cards:

```javascript
// Create threatened species cards
const threatenedGrid = document.getElementById('threatenedGrid');
if (threatenedGrid) {
    const threatenedSpecies = speciesDatabase.filter(s => 
        s.conservation.includes('Endangered') || 
        s.conservation.includes('Vulnerable') || 
        s.conservation.includes('Rare') ||
        s.conservation.includes('Critically')
    ).slice(0, 30);
    
    threatenedGrid.innerHTML = '';
    threatenedSpecies.forEach(s => {
        const card = document.createElement('div');
        card.className = 'specimen-card';
        card.setAttribute('role', 'button');
        card.setAttribute('tabindex', '0');
        card.setAttribute('aria-label', `${s.species} - ${s.conservation} ${s.family}`);
        const statusClass = s.conservation.toLowerCase().replace(/[()]/g, '').replace(/ /g, '-');
        card.innerHTML = `
            <h4><em>${s.species}</em></h4>
            <div class="family">${s.family}</div>
            <p><strong>Habitat:</strong> ${s.habitat}</p>
            <p><span class="conservation ${statusClass}">${s.conservation}</span></p>
            <p><small>${s.morphology.substring(0, 60)}...</small></p>
        `;
        threatenedGrid.appendChild(card);
    });
}
```

Add click handlers right after appending each card (inside the forEach loop, right after threatenedGrid.appendChild(card);):

```javascript
// Add click handler for the card
card.addEventListener('click', function() {
    // Create a modal or expandable section with full details
    // For now, let's just show an alert with the full info
    alert(`
        ${s.species} (${s.family})
        
        Conservation Status: ${s.conservation}
        
        Habitat: ${s.habitat}
        
        Description: ${s.morphology}
    `);
});

// Add keyboard support
card.addEventListener('keypress', function(e) {
    if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') {
        e.preventDefault();
        alert(`
            ${s.species} (${s.family})
            
            Conservation Status: ${s.conservation}
            
            Habitat: ${s.habitat}
            
            Description: ${s.morphology}
        `);
    }
});
```

If you want something more elegant than an alert, you could create a modal or expand the card. Here's a simple expandable version:

```javascript
// Add click handler for the card
card.addEventListener('click', function() {
    // Toggle expanded view
    const existingDetail = card.querySelector('.card-detail');
    if (existingDetail) {
        existingDetail.remove();
    } else {
        const detailDiv = document.createElement('div');
        detailDiv.className = 'card-detail';
        detailDiv.style.marginTop = '10px';
        detailDiv.style.padding = '10px';
        detailDiv.style.backgroundColor = '#f9f9f9';
        detailDiv.style.borderRadius = '4px';
        detailDiv.innerHTML = `
            <p><strong>Full Description:</strong> ${s.morphology}</p>
            <p><strong>Habitat Details:</strong> ${s.habitat}</p>
        `;
        card.appendChild(detailDiv);
    }
});
```

Also, add this CSS for the card detail (add to your style section):

```css
.card-detail {
    margin-top: 10px;
    padding: 10px;
    background-color: #f9f9f9;
    border-radius: 4px;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--primary-color);
    animation: slideDown 0.3s ease;
}

@keyframes slideDown {
    from {
        opacity: 0;
        transform: translateY(-10px);
    }
    to {
        opacity: 1;
        transform: translateY(0);
    }
}
```

The issue was that the cards were created dynamically but never had click event listeners attached to them. The fix above adds both mouse click and keyboard support for accessibility.
